title: Final running order for the Advance Auto Parts Clash at Daytona
text: Feb 19, 2017 at 1:24p ET 0Shares The first race of the 2017 Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series season is now officially in the books, as Joey Logano made a last-lap pass to win Sunday’s rain-delayed 75-lap Advance Auto Parts Clash at Daytona International Speedway. Here is where all 17 drivers finished in the Clash. Getty Images Getty Images 1 Joey Logano Two years ago, Logano drove the No. 22 Team Penske Ford to the victory in the Daytona 500. This time, he did it in the Advance Auto Parts Clash, taking the lead away on the last lap. Getty Images Getty Images 2 Kyle Busch Runner-up was a good result for Busch, although he was frustrated he and Alex Bowman didn’t hook up on the final lap to run down winner Joey Logano. , LAT Images www.latphoto.co.uk Russell LaBounty 3 Alex Bowman Subbing for Dale Earnhardt Jr., Bowman did an excellent job to bring the No. 88 Hendrick Motorsports Chevrolet home in third. , LAT Images www.latphoto.co.uk Michael L. Levitt 4 Danica Patrick Great finish for Patrick, who got the best result of the three Stewart-Haas Racing Fords in the field. Her first top-five finish, although not in a points race. , LAT Images www.latimages.co.uk Nigel Kinrade 5 Kevin Harvick A three-time Clash winner, Harvick got a hard-earned top five in Stewart-Haas Racing’s first race with Ford. , LAT Images www.latimages.co.uk Nigel Kinrade 6 Brad Keselowski The 2012 NASCAR champion made a bold move on then-leader Denny Hamlin on the last lap but got chopped by the Toyota driver. , LAT images www.latphoto.co.uk Matthew T. Thacker 7 Chase Elliott Early on, Elliott struggled badly, so to finish seventh really was pretty good, all things considered. , LAT Images www.latimages.co.uk Nigel Kinrade 8 Daniel Suarez The first Cup race for Suarez was a good one, as he had his Toyota up near the front for much of the race. , LAT Images www.latimages.co.uk Nigel Kinrade 9 Chris Buescher In his first Clash and his first race with JTG-Daugherty Racing, Buescher did very well to come home in the top 10. , LAT Images www.latimages.co.uk Nigel Kinrade 10 Jamie McMurray One of the sport’s best restrictor-plate racers in the sport, McMurray got a decent finish. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 11 Matt Kenseth All the Joe Gibbs Racing Toyotas were fast, including Kenseth, who won this race two years ago. , LAT Images www.latimages.co.uk Nigel Kinrade 12 Dillon ran in the top five late, but couldn’t stay there at the end. , LAT Images www.latphoto.co.uk Michael L. Levitt 13 Denny Hamlin He had the lead going into the last lap, but Brad Keselowski got a run on Hamlin, who tried unsuccessfully to throw the block. , LAT Images www.latimages.co.uk Nigel Kinrade 14 Kyle Larson Contact from Martin Truex Jr. late in the race sent Larson to the garage, which meant he was knocked out of the race. , LAT Images www.latimages.co.uk Nigel Kinrade 15 Martin Truex Jr. With about 15 laps to go, Truex came down on Kyle Larson heading into Turn 3, which resulted in Truex making contact, going into the wall and out of the race. 16 Jimmie Johnson Yet another bad Clash for the seven-time champion, who in the opening 20 laps got loose and put Kurt Busch into the frontstretch wall. Then Johnson crashed himself out on Lap 50 17 Kurt Busch The 2011 race-winner made it just 17 laps before getting clipped by Jimmie Johnson coming out of Turn 4 and knocked out of the race. Getty Images Getty Images
